 not intensify positional competitions for the long-term equilibrium as
 they do in the short-term.
 Thus a consumer may strive for more mobility in the short-term as income
 differences rise, but if the long-equilibrium were to move from a low-income
 differences (income inequality) setting to a higher income-differences
 setting, it is possible that poor consumer withdraws from the positional
 competition (zero status investment).
 The long-term equilibrium conditions of population stability imply a dynamics
 where wider income differences may act to reduce positional investment
 by making band-promotion more difficult (for the poor consumers) and band-secur
ity cheaper (for the richer consumers).
 Similarly, a narrowing of income-differences in the long-term increases
 the value of (utility from) the expenditure towards status for poorer consumers
 - so that the poorer consumers spend less on status investments while the
 richer consumers raise their expenditure towards status to maintain their
 position of wealth in the long-term.
 Inequality can thus have a separating effect of pushing investments away
 from each other in the long-term and eventually discouraging positional
 investments.
 Further, the asset accumulation can either decline or rise with inequality
 depending on the transition functions - so long as the population stability
 criterion is maintained.
\end_layout

