\begin_layout Standard
Every consumer strives to achieve the highest assets in the economy.
 Since the disposable income 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{k}$
\end_inset

 in every band can be used to accumulate towards assets under risk of loss
 or participate in tournaments of unobserved ability, the wealth differences
 among consumers in this economy arise only due to their outcome of the
 promotions or demotions over time.
 These promotions or demotions are what represent the position competition
 in the model that may arise due to institutional arrangements granting
 some mobility across income bands while not completely getting rid of the
 stratification that limits participation.
 In other words, the success in these positional competitions serves simultaneou
sly as both an evidence of ability and a barrier to entry.
 Since we treat economic and social status as the same, the notion of status
 (or ability) is relevant only through probabilistic monetary success in
 the long-term that is revealed to the consumer only through positional
 competitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is evident that differences in income across bands makes the the competition
 biased in favour of the higher income band, so that more expenditure towards
 status increases the probability of one's successes in the competitions
 through the function 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{k}(\nu)$
\end_inset

