\begin_layout Standard
The selection of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 rests upon two properties that we have briefly discussed.
 First, the status competitions can never guarantee a reward to the next
 band i.e.
\begin_inset Formula $\nexists\nu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Second, that any consumer with a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 should be rewarded with a higher probability than a consumer with a lower
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\nu_{1}>\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})>W(\nu_{2})$
\end_inset

 and equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{1})<L(\nu_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\nu_{1}>\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these specifications, we assume a logistic form for 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})$
\end_inset

 as a general formulation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W(\nu) & =\frac{1}{1+e^{-\omega(\nu-\text{\underbar{\ensuremath{\omega}}})}}\label{eq:particular_W_nu_definition}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above specification only considers 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial W}{\partial\nu}$
\end_inset

 is symmetrical around 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the probability to rise to the next band rises and drops at the same rate
 around 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The same applies to the equivalent definition for 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

.
 When considering the population stability in band, the above specification
 translates into a simple linear relationship between the parameters that
 we discuss below.
 While a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial W}{\partial\nu}$
\end_inset

 that is asymmetrical around 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

 may provide a more general specification of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

, the results that we derive from the specification are independent of whether
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial W}{\partial\nu}$
\end_inset

 is symmetrical around 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

 around or not.
\end_layout

